headline: Did former President Barack Obama lose the Democratic presidential debate?

utterances.speaker: JUAN WILLIAMS, CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: Hello, everyone. I'm Juan Williams along with Emily Compagno, Brian Kilmeade, Dana Perino, and Greg, Greg Gutfeld.  It's 5 o'clock in New York City, this is "The Five." 2020 Democrats ducking it out in Detroit during the second debate.  President Trump is on his way to a rally tonight in Cincinnati, and just moments ago he went after the Democrats. We're going to show it to you in just a bit. But first, the attacks were fierce and they were plentiful on the debate stage. And Joe Biden, once again, he was enemy number one.

utterances.speaker: SEN. KAMALA HARRIS
utterances.sentences: When Vice President Biden was on the United States Senate working with segregationists to oppose busting --

utterances.speaker: SEN. CORY BOOKER
utterances.sentences: If you want to compare records and, frankly, I'm shocked that you do, I am happy to do that.

utterances.speaker: MAYOR BILL DE BLASIO
utterances.sentences: Did you say those deportations were good idea? Or did you go to the president and say this is a mistake? We shouldn't do it, which one?

utterances.speaker: SEN. KIRSTEN GILLIBRAND
utterances.sentences: What did you mean when you said when a woman works outside the home it's resulting in, quote, the deterioration of family?

utterances.speaker: BOOKER
utterances.sentences: Mr. Vice President, there's a saying in my community, dip it into Kool Aid and you don't even know the flavor.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Well, one of the most talked about moments was Tulsi Gabbard's takedown of Kamala Harris' record as a prosecutor.

utterances.speaker: REP. TULSI GABBARD
utterances.sentences: She put over 1,500 people in jail for marijuana violations and then laughed about it when she was asked if she ever smoked marijuana. In the case of those who are on death row, innocent people, you actually blocked evidence from being revealed that would have freed them until you were forced to do so. There's no excuse for that. And the people who've suffered under your rein as prosecutor, you owe them an apology.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: And the debate proved no one was safe from attack, and that included President Obama.

utterances.speaker: JOE BIDEN
utterances.sentences: Obamacare is working.

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.sentences: Your plan does not cover everyone in America.  JULIÁN CASTRO: First of all, Mr. Vice President, it looks like one of us has learned the lessons of the past and one of us hasn't.

utterances.speaker: DE BLASIO
utterances.sentences: Mr. Vice President, tell us what did you do to try and spur on the Justice Department to --

utterances.speaker: BOOKER
utterances.sentences: Mr. Vice President, you can't have it both ways. You invoke President Obama more than anybody in this campaign. You can't do it when it's convenient and then dodge it when it's not.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Dana, did President Obama lose the debate?

utterances.speaker: DANA PERINO, CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: I think that if President Obama had been on the stage in the last two nights, he would have been considered a conservative Democrat and a moderate. And the way that this -- the field have shifted so far to the left that President Obama will -- wait a minute, we're still for border security, right? Are we just, like, whoa, stop everybody. Now, what he did have that I didn't see a ton of last night is the charisma, the hope, the lift, right? You saw Dan Bowles of the Washington Post writes today that the Democrats put their worse face forward the last two nights. President Obama when he was running, he was -- remember he was the happy guy. Hope and change. And you didn't really feel any of that on the stage. I also think that instead of going after President Trump, like, I know -- I understand they kind of -- they did go -- they always go after President Trump, but the focus was on that the last eight years was not progressive enough and that they didn't go far enough, and there has to be some drastic change. Look at what Elizabeth Warren is saying, and Bernie Sanders. You might expect it from them.  But I would imagine that Joe Biden didn't expect that from Kamala Harris.  To Cory Booker's point about Biden clinging to Obama when it's useful for him and distancing when it's not, it's pretty effective and I think that's why he got the applause that he did.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Greg, if you had to pick somebody out, and I know you watched everything --

utterances.speaker: GREG GUTFELD, CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: Every minute of it.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Right.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: You bet.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Who would you say won?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Oh, I say -- the most memorable would be Tulsi. She kamalad Kamala. I mean, if Joe Biden was Tanya Harding, Tulsi was Shawn Eckhardt.  And he just hitting Kamala in the knee -- or it was basically Nancy Kerrigan. I mean, it was the most memorable thing. I do have --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Wait a second. Who's Shawn Eckhardt?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: The guy that hit Kerrigan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: By the way, I was asking you -- wait a second, because I thought, and I'm going to get roundly criticized, but she was a fashion statement last night.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: You cannot comment on her clothing. Is it because it's white, Juan? No. So, you know what, a couple of things. One, I don't like audience -- I don't like the audience reaction to things because they react to what is interesting or exciting and not what's important. So when somebody zings somebody you get this -- like the Kool Aid line that Cory used. Wasn't that creative or interesting? But it felt like it needed applause.  To your point, in 2009, President Obama was seen as a progressive hero, ten years later he's now considered a Republican. And Obamacare is a right- wing plot. But the attacks on Obama reflect an actual fact that Trump is only been president for three years, the major problems that they're discussing, whether it's immigration or health care, happened -- let's talk deficits and drugs --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Decades.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: It's been decades. So, it just seems like maybe they're right that they have to talk about -- they have to go past Trump. He's only been there for three years, not even that.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: So, Emily, that -- you know, you pick up on the vibe of reading things. Dana and I were talking earlier on her show. And right now the consensus seems to be that if you put the two nights together, the winner was Elizabeth Warren, do you agree?

utterances.speaker: EMILY COMPAGNO, GUEST CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: I think there's a strong argument I think for that, and that she had the most polished, kind of the pro out there. I think that in terms of that galvanizing quality that you were taking about, I actually think it was Bernie Sanders from yesterday. I think last night there was a lot of ruffled feathers, a lot of, kind of, disheveled -- and it wasn't that kind of smooth delivery.   Other than, actually, Cory Booker who surprised me, and interestingly among my circle he was the most, like, annoying to a lot of people, and yet his delivery I thought was --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Oh, no. There was somebody else who was much more annoying.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Who?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: De Blasio.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Oh, yeah.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: You always say --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I know. You know, I try to block him out of my brain.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Actually -- what do you say? Tax the hell out of Iraq.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: I do think the most effective attack of the night, though, was when Tulsi did go after Kamala. And it was clear, it was concise, it was without drama or histrionics, and she was correct. And Kamala only had the defense of -- well, I'm proud of what I did. But especially in California, and especially -- you know, given her record there, she flip-flopped over the line between backing the blue and really, you know, being that kind of fan of that liberal community for a lot of years. And she has to answer for it, and she has not in a clear way. That death penalty evidence case was a big deal to Californians. And to me, I thought she was going to shine but she failed.

utterances.speaker: BRIAN KILMEADE, GUEST CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: My thing is -- and Juan, do you want to ask me if -- do you want to call on me?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: No, I expected you to pop up.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Once again, he's trying to turn this into "Fox & Friends."

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: There you go.

utterances.speaker: KILMEADE
utterances.sentences: Two things, there were two time bombs in place. One was the Kamala Harris. Tulsi Gabbard outlined the problems. They're all sync in, they were not denied. This is time for people to go and probe that out.  She's -- any good reporter anchor is going to say, you have to defend this.  Go ahead and defend this. Number two is -- tell me what kind of mayor you were, Cory Booker? What were you doing on crime? What did you do for the area? What did you do for gangs? What kind of report card do you have? So Joe Biden said, yeah, I kind of want this fight. Cory Booker had a great line. People applauded, we move on. But this is legitimate farter for anybody he sits down and talks to him. Number two, I happened to read that Joe Manchin, John Tester, Mark Warner, as well as Jeanne Shaheen, all Democrats who said these people on the stage are not reflecting what I think what Democrats stand for. We're not for Medicare for all, we're not for opening up the border and letting people waltz in, or decriminalizing. You know, we're not for a lot what -- most of the people are getting applause for. So there's a problem.  The Democrats got to have a therapist, find out what they stand for. I don't know why Elizabeth Warren would stand out? She's smart, she's confident, she's concise, but what she stands for is not going to get her elected nationwide, because the country is not there.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I think the country is there, by the way. I think, if you talk about Medicare for all, if you talk about education --

utterances.speaker: KILMEADE
utterances.sentences: It's not affordable.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Guess what? Just go look at the polls. People like this stuff.  Now, Dana makes the point --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: We all like free stuff.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: You can break it down. You can say, hey, you'll lose your private coverage, but she has --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: No, no, no.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: I do think -- can I make two tactical points?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: So Kamala Harris made a decision because she had been on every side of the health care issue, they decided two days before this debate to release her health care plan. I don't think that was a good idea because she kind of knew it, but not really. And -- but -- all of her opponents knew it and they went right after her. Now, she takes it as a compliment that she was getting all of this heat because she's considered one of the front runners, but I think that that was a bit of a mistake. And you want to know how you can tell. Today, she came out after the debate, she held a press conference for about 45 minutes, took as many questions as she could, and I think that was to reassure her supporters and the people sending checks to her campaign that she's got this. She might have had a rocky debate, but she still wants to be considered a front runner.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Juan, can I make another tactical point?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Yep.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I believe the Democrats better do something because they're starting to look like the donner party. Like they're just starting to eat each other, you know. It's like that -- they've got to start shedding some weight from that lifeboat, like that soccer team in the mountains, because they're turning -- they have no choice but to turn on each other, so they've got -- they got to start throwing people overboard.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Meanwhile, President Obama is like, why are you turning on me?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yeah, exactly.

utterances.speaker: KILMEADE
utterances.sentences: Of all the soccer stories that's the one I don't like where they eat each other.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yeah, that's my favorite one.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Brian, they are going to start throwing people overboard for September. Who doesn't make it?

utterances.speaker: KILMEADE
utterances.sentences: Well, I mean, right now, there's only seven that qualify. And de Blasio, I think, could start walking home. Clearly, Tulsi Gabbard has long legs, but she definitely has done things enough that people are intrigue enough to get her that that donner threshold. I know we're being wrap. I am not sure if -- I'm not sure if they get over ten. I would love to see a ten or less, so we get into one night.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: Gillibrand struck me as the super outlier, even more that she already has --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: What did she do? I can't remember.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: The attack -- remember I've said that she was going to have some obscure attack from his past? They went after him. The things he wrote in 1980 -- we talked about it.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yeah, yeah, yeah. Then it was like -- it was basically about family stuff, and he's like -- he had the hardest family life of all.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: And she was saying, you don't think women should be -- belong in a work place. Like, nobody believed that.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I think it was distortion of it of what the piece said. Anyway, breaking news about the Justice Department, they are not prosecuting former FBI Director Jim Comey over leaking classified memos about President Trump.  Critics now saying he's getting a free pass. Details straight ahead right here on THE FIVE.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: A big development in Washington, sources confirming to Fox News that the Justice Department will not prosecute James Comey for leaking classifies memos about his interactions with President Trump, now this despite the DOJ inspector general referring the fired FBI director for possible prosecution. Now, you may remember back in 2017, Comey told Congress he purposely leaked the sensitive memos to the media, through a friend, so that Special Counsel Robert Mueller would be appointed. Brian, I want to go to you first. The -- you've been talking about a shoelace for an hour.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: That was a commercial break. Commercial break.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: No, we just say you're a blowhard.

utterances.speaker: KILMEADE
utterances.sentences: That's true. I talked too much. I like the breaks better than show. Go ahead, Dana. Do you have a question? Sorry about that.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: One of the accusations about Comey was that he wanted to get these classified memos that he wrote out and he launders it through his friend, it was a professor -- I knew you could talk about this. You even know all the names.

utterances.speaker: KILMEADE
utterances.sentences: So he gets it out, and he gives it out, and they put it in the New York Times. Next thing you know it's a special counsel victory. But it turns out the FBI comes and visit him again to get other memos. What I find mysterious -- and I don't know the answer to this, maybe you guys do.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I don't.

utterances.speaker: KILMEADE
utterances.sentences: The FBI showed up at his house to get a memo, to take a memo that he wrote the night before. Did he call and turn himself in about a secret memo? What I find this word intent fascinating, I'm not a lawyer, but if I speed -- if I was going 85 in a 55 but I didn't intend to do so, I'm still getting a ticket. It said he didn't intend to give out confidential memos because it wasn't labeled confidential when he gave them out.

utterances.speaker: KILMEADE
utterances.sentences: Anybody knows confidential memos -- he's the director of the FBI, he knows when he sees it, because he wrote it about the president. If anything that's confidential, it's that.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Emily, was he driving 85 in a 55 limit?

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: The difference there that that's a strict liability crime, right? Which means it doesn't matter what your intent was. And here, I think the overarching point --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Take that, Brian.

utterances.speaker: KILMEADE
utterances.sentences: I know. I'm not liking the show at all today. This is going terrible for me.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: Guys. And I think -- I think here overarching strategy is most important, which is that -- this would have been the first case that the DOJ prosecuted of a Russian investigator, essentially, right? The Russian investigation investigator. And this is kind of a thin margin for them, and it would be difficult for them to prosecute, right?  They came out and source said it was all about the intent, so I think it's actually tactically wiser that they're holding back, and I want viewers to understand that Comey is not in the clear, right? He's potentially the target --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Why?

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: Because the FISA abuse investigation is ongoing by the I.G. And also, and more importantly, the DOJ and the Connecticut U.S. attorney, John Durham, are currently investigating the investigator as A.G. Barr said in May this year, and the power to compel and the investigation power that Durham has exceeds I.H. Horowitz by a ton. So look for there to be more evidence if something, or a lot more culpability around the corner. This is totally OK.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Please, you guys. Get off this horse.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: No, I'm serious.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Look, the reality is that the man who is in charge of making this decision is Bill Barr. Come on, Bill Barr is a political player on the Trump team and he said this wasn't even close. He said it wasn't even close. And yet, you have people who want to play tribal politics saying, oh, yeah, this is a double standard. Why is he being held? Look, let's look at that memo --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Oh, please. The memo -- the memo said it was not classified at the time it was given to the professor.

utterances.speaker: KILMEADE
utterances.sentences: -- classified. Isn't he the FBI director?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: That's right. And so he can decide what's classified and what's not classified. And the second thing --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: The guy wasn't the president. He was in transition as president-elect. And the second thing to say here is if it was Donald Trump Jr., and we had no instinct about intent, he would be on the -- right now. The only reason that he didn't get indicted from my understanding in the Mueller report is --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: For people out there who have been driving -- got pick up because they're driving 85 and a 55, even if they didn't intend to, they're getting the ticket. But Huma Abedin, Hillary Clinton, James Comey, nobody else gets in trouble.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: You know -- a genius, I may be wrong on this. Emily is the lawyer, not me. But speaking of Huma and Hillary, Comey set his own precedent by not indicting Hillary. So it's like -- he set a precedent for him to go free. Hillary wasn't indicted. It's like a politician decriminalizing pot before he buys a marijuana dispensary. Is that legally --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: That's like insider trading.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yeah. I think I might be completely wrong, but it sounds right.  But I also have to agree with Juan a bit, I mean, Bill -- is it Bill Barr who made this decision. And I don't want to be like the anti-Trumpers who live in the past. I like to think about the future, you know -- you know, I know that there's a lot of wrongdoing on both sides, but on that side, especially, but --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Like Andrew Yang last night, he was talking about the future.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I like talking about the future.

utterances.speaker: KILMEADE
utterances.sentences: And you know in the future we all should give up our routing numbers because a thousand dollar a month --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Guess what? In the future we're going to come back from this commercial break. Elijah Cummings is being called a hypocrite over a video showing him calling Baltimore drug-infested. You'll see it next.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Don't you hate it when people say terrible, racist things about Baltimore?

utterances.speaker: REP. ELIJAH CUMMINGS
utterances.sentences: This morning, I left my community of Baltimore, a drug- infested area where a lot of the drugs that we're talking about today, have already taken the lives of so many children. The same children that I watched 14 or 15 years ago as they grew up now walking around like zombies.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: That was 20 years ago when Cummings accurately pointed out the true devastation of that city. Other than pumping billions of dollars, what has anybody done about it since then? Well, I know what I did, I watched The Wire, just like a bunch of other white people did. This fantastic show depicted the horrors of Baltimore's drug problem, back before drugs became a lifestyle choice, -- like Al Sharpton. It was a big favorite among white educated people, especially liberals who felt by watching The Wire and talking about it, it solved Baltimore's problems. Sort of the way "Game of Thrones" solved the nation's dragon problem. So art could eliminate a problem, but it could also pretend to be a solution. Everyone watches a show and feels better about themselves, it's virtue signaling with popcorn and a remote, you never have to leave your couch, but at least you've done something, which is more than Trump can say, he probably never watched "The Wire." So "The Wire" won tons of awards and is considered a classic. And for two decades the city it depicts declines even more. I applaud Cummings for his frankness, but wonder how despite all the money shoveled into that district, none of the problems depicted so starkly in "The Wire," the drugs, the debt, the corruption, were fixed. Meanwhile, Cummings is a millionaire, another in a long line of liberal Democrats who have work hard and become rich people. Maybe HBO can do a TV series about that, too. I don't have any real questions.

utterances.speaker: KILMEADE
utterances.sentences: You pretty much answered all your questions.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I answered all my questions.

utterances.speaker: KILMEADE
utterances.sentences: I will say this, to say that Elijah Cummings' home got broken in to --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Boy, I didn't know that

utterances.speaker: KILMEADE
utterances.sentences: -- Saturday. It got broken into like 3:40 in the morning.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: No idea.

utterances.speaker: KILMEADE
utterances.sentences: No idea if it's related. We have not heard much from him through this entire process.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: It's not a home. He lives in this one and he rents out.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Oh.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: I don't know anything about that. But it's not the home that he actually lives in.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Can I --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Sure. Yes, please, though

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Because I don't get this. I mean, it's like saying, you know, I'm a big fan of The Sopranos. Do I think that New Jersey is filled with mafia -- I don't get it? But anyway, the second thing is --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I could respond to that, but go ahead.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: The second thing to say is, what this really is about is President Trump who went after Cummings because he doesn't like Cummings exercising oversight, especially on things like, let me see your tax returns, why is there families being separated at the border. He says --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: He called them out for what I think most Americans think is just terrible, terrible behavior.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: But I would say this, why does Trump talk about drug-infested Baltimore and not drug-infested --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: New Hampshire.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: -- of New Hampshire, Vermont --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: He did.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: -- Ohio. I mean, where white Americans being decimated --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: He actually --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: -- he doesn't say that.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: He's actually trying to solve the opioid problem in all those areas.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: And that's what Elijah Cummings was doing in that clip you played. He's saying, listen, we have a problem with drugs and kids --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Twenty years ago.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: -- used to love, now are zombies from drugs. We, Americans --we can do -- Trump talks about white America in rural areas that are hard-hit by the opioids, and he said, you know, we're Americans, we can solve our problem, but doesn't talk that way about black America.

utterances.speaker: KILMEADE
utterances.sentences: He says -- he even told Ben Carson -- Ben Carson, presser yesterday, you would know this well, where he says I'm talking to the president, he wants to help out. He would even meet with Elijah Cummings himself. I think he wants to solve the problem. I was talking to Dana today on the show, and I think this thing could turn out for the better.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: The coalition of African-American pastors meeting with Trump, and they're going to Baltimore?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: These are moments when you can actually have an opportunity to do something. And if the president is willing to meet -- you could probably do something. Here's something, though, this has been going on for a long time.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Elijah Cummings talked about that in 1999, that's 20 years ago, it's 2019. A lot of this can't necessarily be fixed by the government.  The government can throw money at things, but it's not actually a government thing, this is a deeper problem, and we should get Marianne Williamson on it.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Oh, she'll get Bill Pulte.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Yeah. There's a lot of things, it's not just the government.  It's --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Bill Pulte, I think, is already -- is looking at Baltimore.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: -- St. Louis with the dude from twitter. And he, obviously --

utterances.speaker: KILMEADE
utterances.sentences: They flag down houses and rebuild --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes, the blight authority.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: As a constituent on the West Coast, my biggest issue with this is that the taking offense trigger blocks the actual facts.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Good point.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: Because the reality is a blight on government, right. utterances.utterance: What did you mean when you said when a woman works outside the home it's resulting in, quote, the deterioration of family?

utterances.speaker: BOOKER
utterances.utterance: Mr. Vice President, there's a saying in my community, dip it into Kool Aid and you don't even know the flavor.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, one of the most talked about moments was Tulsi Gabbard's takedown of Kamala Harris' record as a prosecutor.

utterances.speaker: REP. TULSI GABBARD
utterances.utterance: She put over 1,500 people in jail for marijuana violations and then laughed about it when she was asked if she ever smoked marijuana. In the case of those who are on death row, innocent people, you actually blocked evidence from being revealed that would have freed them until you were forced to do so. There's no excuse for that. And the people who've suffered under your rein as prosecutor, you owe them an apology.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: And the debate proved no one was safe from attack, and that included President Obama.

utterances.speaker: JOE BIDEN
utterances.utterance: Obamacare is working.

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.utterance: Your plan does not cover everyone in America. JULIÁN CASTRO: First of all, Mr. Vice President, it looks like one of us has learned the lessons of the past and one of us hasn't.

utterances.speaker: DE BLASIO
utterances.utterance: Mr. Vice President, tell us what did you do to try and spur on the Justice Department to --

utterances.speaker: BOOKER
utterances.utterance: Mr. Vice President, you can't have it both ways. You invoke President Obama more than anybody in this campaign. You can't do it when it's convenient and then dodge it when it's not.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Dana, did President Obama lose the debate?

utterances.speaker: DANA PERINO, CO-HOST
utterances.utterance: I think that if President Obama had been on the stage in the last two nights, he would have been considered a conservative Democrat and a moderate. And the way that this -- the field have shifted so far to the left that President Obama will -- wait a minute, we're still for border security, right? Are we just, like, whoa, stop everybody. Now, what he did have that I didn't see a ton of last night is the charisma, the hope, the lift, right? You saw Dan Bowles of the Washington Post writes today that the Democrats put their worse face forward the last two nights. President Obama when he was running, he was -- remember he was the happy guy. Hope and change. And you didn't really feel any of that on the stage. I also think that instead of going after President Trump, like, I know -- I understand they kind of -- they did go -- they always go after President Trump, but the focus was on that the last eight years was not progressive enough and that they didn't go far enough, and there has to be some drastic change. Look at what Elizabeth Warren is saying, and Bernie Sanders. You might expect it from them. But I would imagine that Joe Biden didn't expect that from Kamala Harris.  To Cory Booker's point about Biden clinging to Obama when it's useful for him and distancing when it's not, it's pretty effective and I think that's why he got the applause that he did.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Greg, if you had to pick somebody out, and I know you watched everything --

utterances.speaker: GREG GUTFELD, CO-HOST
utterances.utterance: Every minute of it.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You bet.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Who would you say won?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Oh, I say -- the most memorable would be Tulsi. She kamalad Kamala. I mean, if Joe Biden was Tanya Harding, Tulsi was Shawn Eckhardt.  And he just hitting Kamala in the knee -- or it was basically Nancy Kerrigan. I mean, it was the most memorable thing. I do have --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Wait a second. Who's Shawn Eckhardt?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: The guy that hit Kerrigan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: By the way, I was asking you -- wait a second, because I thought, and I'm going to get roundly criticized, but she was a fashion statement last night.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You cannot comment on her clothing. Is it because it's white, Juan? No. So, you know what, a couple of things. One, I don't like audience -- I don't like the audience reaction to things because they react to what is interesting or exciting and not what's important. So when somebody zings somebody you get this -- like the Kool Aid line that Cory used. Wasn't that creative or interesting? But it felt like it needed applause. To your point, in 2009, President Obama was seen as a progressive hero, ten years later he's now considered a Republican. And Obamacare is a right- wing plot. But the attacks on Obama reflect an actual fact that Trump is only been president for three years, the major problems that they're discussing, whether it's immigration or health care, happened -- let's talk deficits and drugs --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Decades.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: It's been decades. So, it just seems like maybe they're right that they have to talk about -- they have to go past Trump. He's only been there for three years, not even that.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: So, Emily, that -- you know, you pick up on the vibe of reading things. Dana and I were talking earlier on her show. And right now the consensus seems to be that if you put the two nights together, the winner was Elizabeth Warren, do you agree?

utterances.speaker: EMILY COMPAGNO, GUEST CO-HOST
utterances.utterance: I think there's a strong argument I think for that, and that she had the most polished, kind of the pro out there. I think that in terms of that galvanizing quality that you were taking about, I actually think it was Bernie Sanders from yesterday. I think last night there was a lot of ruffled feathers, a lot of, kind of, disheveled -- and it wasn't that kind of smooth delivery. Other than, actually, Cory Booker who surprised me, and interestingly among my circle he was the most, like, annoying to a lot of people, and yet his delivery I thought was --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Oh, no. There was somebody else who was much more annoying.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Who?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: De Blasio.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Oh, yeah.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: You always say --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I know. You know, I try to block him out of my brain.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Actually -- what do you say? Tax the hell out of Iraq.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: I do think the most effective attack of the night, though, was when Tulsi did go after Kamala. And it was clear, it was concise, it was without drama or histrionics, and she was correct. And Kamala only had the defense of -- well, I'm proud of what I did. But especially in California, and especially -- you know, given her record there, she flip-flopped over the line between backing the blue and really, you know, being that kind of fan of that liberal community for a lot of years. And she has to answer for it, and she has not in a clear way. That death penalty evidence case was a big deal to Californians. And to me, I thought she was going to shine but she failed.

utterances.speaker: BRIAN KILMEADE, GUEST CO-HOST
utterances.utterance: My thing is -- and Juan, do you want to ask me if -- do you want to call on me?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: No, I expected you to pop up.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Once again, he's trying to turn this into "Fox & Friends."

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: There you go.

utterances.speaker: KILMEADE
utterances.utterance: Two things, there were two time bombs in place. One was the Kamala Harris. Tulsi Gabbard outlined the problems. They're all sync in, they were not denied. This is time for people to go and probe that out.  She's -- any good reporter anchor is going to say, you have to defend this.  Go ahead and defend this. Number two is -- tell me what kind of mayor you were, Cory Booker? What were you doing on crime? What did you do for the area? What did you do for gangs? What kind of report card do you have? So Joe Biden said, yeah, I kind of want this fight. Cory Booker had a great line. People applauded, we move on. But this is legitimate farter for anybody he sits down and talks to him. Number two, I happened to read that Joe Manchin, John Tester, Mark Warner, as well as Jeanne Shaheen, all Democrats who said these people on the stage are not reflecting what I think what Democrats stand for. We're not for Medicare for all, we're not for opening up the border and letting people waltz in, or decriminalizing. You know, we're not for a lot what -- most of the people are getting applause for. So there's a problem.  The Democrats got to have a therapist, find out what they stand for. I don't know why Elizabeth Warren would stand out? She's smart, she's confident, she's concise, but what she stands for is not going to get her elected nationwide, because the country is not there.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I think the country is there, by the way. I think, if you talk about Medicare for all, if you talk about education --

utterances.speaker: KILMEADE
utterances.utterance: It's not affordable.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Guess what? Just go look at the polls. People like this stuff.  Now, Dana makes the point --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: We all like free stuff.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: You can break it down. You can say, hey, you'll lose your private coverage, but she has --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: No, no, no.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I do think -- can I make two tactical points?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: So Kamala Harris made a decision because she had been on every side of the health care issue, they decided two days before this debate to release her health care plan. I don't think that was a good idea because she kind of knew it, but not really. And -- but -- all of her opponents knew it and they went right after her. Now, she takes it as a compliment that she was getting all of this heat because she's considered one of the front runners, but I think that that was a bit of a mistake. And you want to know how you can tell. Today, she came out after the debate, she held a press conference for about 45 minutes, took as many questions as she could, and I think that was to reassure her supporters and the people sending checks to her campaign that she's got this. She might have had a rocky debate, but she still wants to be considered a front runner.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Juan, can I make another tactical point?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yep.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I believe the Democrats better do something because they're starting to look like the donner party. Like they're just starting to eat each other, you know. It's like that -- they've got to start shedding some weight from that lifeboat, like that soccer team in the mountains, because they're turning -- they have no choice but to turn on each other, so they've got -- they got to start throwing people overboard.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Meanwhile, President Obama is like, why are you turning on me?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah, exactly.

utterances.speaker: KILMEADE
utterances.utterance: Of all the soccer stories that's the one I don't like where they eat each other.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah, that's my favorite one.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Brian, they are going to start throwing people overboard for September. Who doesn't make it?

utterances.speaker: KILMEADE
utterances.utterance: Well, I mean, right now, there's only seven that qualify. And de Blasio, I think, could start walking home. Clearly, Tulsi Gabbard has long legs, but she definitely has done things enough that people are intrigue enough to get her that that donner threshold. I know we're being wrap. I am not sure if -- I'm not sure if they get over ten. I would love to see a ten or less, so we get into one night.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: Gillibrand struck me as the super outlier, even more that she already has --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: What did she do? I can't remember.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: The attack -- remember I've said that she was going to have some obscure attack from his past? They went after him. The things he wrote in 1980 -- we talked about it.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah, yeah, yeah. Then it was like -- it was basically about family stuff, and he's like -- he had the hardest family life of all.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: And she was saying, you don't think women should be -- belong in a work place. Like, nobody believed that.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I think it was distortion of it of what the piece said. Anyway, breaking news about the Justice Department, they are not prosecuting former FBI Director Jim Comey over leaking classified memos about President Trump.  Critics now saying he's getting a free pass. Details straight ahead right here on THE FIVE.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: A big development in Washington, sources confirming to Fox News that the Justice Department will not prosecute James Comey for leaking classifies memos about his interactions with President Trump, now this despite the DOJ inspector general referring the fired FBI director for possible prosecution. Now, you may remember back in 2017, Comey told Congress he purposely leaked the sensitive memos to the media, through a friend, so that Special Counsel Robert Mueller would be appointed. Brian, I want to go to you first. The -- you've been talking about a shoelace for an hour.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: That was a commercial break. Commercial break.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: No, we just say you're a blowhard.

utterances.speaker: KILMEADE
utterances.utterance: That's true. I talked too much. I like the breaks better than show. Go ahead, Dana. Do you have a question? Sorry about that.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: One of the accusations about Comey was that he wanted to get these classified memos that he wrote out and he launders it through his friend, it was a professor -- I knew you could talk about this. You even know all the names.

utterances.speaker: KILMEADE
utterances.utterance: So he gets it out, and he gives it out, and they put it in the New York Times. Next thing you know it's a special counsel victory. But it turns out the FBI comes and visit him again to get other memos. What I find mysterious -- and I don't know the answer to this, maybe you guys do.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I don't.

utterances.speaker: KILMEADE
utterances.utterance: The FBI showed up at his house to get a memo, to take a memo that he wrote the night before. Did he call and turn himself in about a secret memo? What I find this word intent fascinating, I'm not a lawyer, but if I speed -- if I was going 85 in a 55 but I didn't intend to do so, I'm still getting a ticket. It said he didn't intend to give out confidential memos because it wasn't labeled confidential when he gave them out.

utterances.speaker: KILMEADE
utterances.utterance: Anybody knows confidential memos -- he's the director of the FBI, he knows when he sees it, because he wrote it about the president. If anything that's confidential, it's that.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Emily, was he driving 85 in a 55 limit?

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: The difference there that that's a strict liability crime, right? Which means it doesn't matter what your intent was. And here, I think the overarching point --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Take that, Brian.

utterances.speaker: KILMEADE
utterances.utterance: I know. I'm not liking the show at all today. This is going terrible for me.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: Guys. And I think -- I think here overarching strategy is most important, which is that -- this would have been the first case that the DOJ prosecuted of a Russian investigator, essentially, right? The Russian investigation investigator. And this is kind of a thin margin for them, and it would be difficult for them to prosecute, right? They came out and source said it was all about the intent, so I think it's actually tactically wiser that they're holding back, and I want viewers to understand that Comey is not in the clear, right? He's potentially the target --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Why?

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: Because the FISA abuse investigation is ongoing by the I.G. And also, and more importantly, the DOJ and the Connecticut U.S. attorney, John Durham, are currently investigating the investigator as A.G. Barr said in May this year, and the power to compel and the investigation power that Durham has exceeds I.H. Horowitz by a ton. So look for there to be more evidence if something, or a lot more culpability around the corner. This is totally OK.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Please, you guys. Get off this horse.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: No, I'm serious.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Look, the reality is that the man who is in charge of making this decision is Bill Barr. Come on, Bill Barr is a political player on the Trump team and he said this wasn't even close. He said it wasn't even close. And yet, you have people who want to play tribal politics saying, oh, yeah, this is a double standard. Why is he being held? Look, let's look at that memo --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Oh, please. The memo -- the memo said it was not classified at the time it was given to the professor.

utterances.speaker: KILMEADE
utterances.utterance: -- classified. Isn't he the FBI director?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: That's right. And so he can decide what's classified and what's not classified. And the second thing --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: The guy wasn't the president. He was in transition as president-elect. And the second thing to say here is if it was Donald Trump Jr., and we had no instinct about intent, he would be on the -- right now. The only reason that he didn't get indicted from my understanding in the Mueller report is --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: For people out there who have been driving -- got pick up because they're driving 85 and a 55, even if they didn't intend to, they're getting the ticket. But Huma Abedin, Hillary Clinton, James Comey, nobody else gets in trouble.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You know -- a genius, I may be wrong on this. Emily is the lawyer, not me. But speaking of Huma and Hillary, Comey set his own precedent by not indicting Hillary. So it's like -- he set a precedent for him to go free. Hillary wasn't indicted. It's like a politician decriminalizing pot before he buys a marijuana dispensary. Is that legally --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: That's like insider trading.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah. I think I might be completely wrong, but it sounds right.  But I also have to agree with Juan a bit, I mean, Bill -- is it Bill Barr who made this decision. And I don't want to be like the anti-Trumpers who live in the past. I like to think about the future, you know -- you know, I know that there's a lot of wrongdoing on both sides, but on that side, especially, but --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Like Andrew Yang last night, he was talking about the future.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I like talking about the future.

utterances.speaker: KILMEADE
utterances.utterance: And you know in the future we all should give up our routing numbers because a thousand dollar a month --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Guess what? In the future we're going to come back from this commercial break. Elijah Cummings is being called a hypocrite over a video showing him calling Baltimore drug-infested. You'll see it next.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Don't you hate it when people say terrible, racist things about Baltimore?

utterances.speaker: REP. ELIJAH CUMMINGS
utterances.utterance: This morning, I left my community of Baltimore, a drug- infested area where a lot of the drugs that we're talking about today, have already taken the lives of so many children. The same children that I watched 14 or 15 years ago as they grew up now walking around like zombies.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: That was 20 years ago when Cummings accurately pointed out the true devastation of that city. Other than pumping billions of dollars, what has anybody done about it since then? Well, I know what I did, I watched The Wire, just like a bunch of other white people did. This fantastic show depicted the horrors of Baltimore's drug problem, back before drugs became a lifestyle choice, -- like Al Sharpton. It was a big favorite among white educated people, especially liberals who felt by watching The Wire and talking about it, it solved Baltimore's problems. Sort of the way "Game of Thrones" solved the nation's dragon problem. So art could eliminate a problem, but it could also pretend to be a solution. Everyone watches a show and feels better about themselves, it's virtue signaling with popcorn and a remote, you never have to leave your couch, but at least you've done something, which is more than Trump can say, he probably never watched "The Wire." So "The Wire" won tons of awards and is considered a classic. And for two decades the city it depicts declines even more. I applaud Cummings for his frankness, but wonder how despite all the money shoveled into that district, none of the problems depicted so starkly in "The Wire," the drugs, the debt, the corruption, were fixed. Meanwhile, Cummings is a millionaire, another in a long line of liberal Democrats who have work hard and become rich people. Maybe HBO can do a TV series about that, too. I don't have any real questions.

utterances.speaker: KILMEADE
utterances.utterance: You pretty much answered all your questions.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I answered all my questions.

utterances.speaker: KILMEADE
utterances.utterance: I will say this, to say that Elijah Cummings' home got broken in to --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Boy, I didn't know that

utterances.speaker: KILMEADE
utterances.utterance: -- Saturday. It got broken into like 3:40 in the morning.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: No idea.

utterances.speaker: KILMEADE
utterances.utterance: No idea if it's related. We have not heard much from him through this entire process.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: It's not a home. He lives in this one and he rents out.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Oh.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I don't know anything about that. But it's not the home that he actually lives in.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Can I --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Sure. Yes, please, though

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Because I don't get this. I mean, it's like saying, you know, I'm a big fan of The Sopranos. Do I think that New Jersey is filled with mafia -- I don't get it? But anyway, the second thing is --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I could respond to that, but go ahead.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: The second thing to say is, what this really is about is President Trump who went after Cummings because he doesn't like Cummings exercising oversight, especially on things like, let me see your tax returns, why is there families being separated at the border. He says --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: He called them out for what I think most Americans think is just terrible, terrible behavior.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: But I would say this, why does Trump talk about drug-infested Baltimore and not drug-infested --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: New Hampshire.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: -- of New Hampshire, Vermont --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: He did.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: -- Ohio. I mean, where white Americans being decimated --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: He actually --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: -- he doesn't say that.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: He's actually trying to solve the opioid problem in all those areas.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: And that's what Elijah Cummings was doing in that clip you played. He's saying, listen, we have a problem with drugs and kids --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Twenty years ago.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: -- used to love, now are zombies from drugs. We, Americans --we can do -- Trump talks about white America in rural areas that are hard-hit by the opioids, and he said, you know, we're Americans, we can solve our problem, but doesn't talk that way about black America.

utterances.speaker: KILMEADE
utterances.utterance: He says -- he even told Ben Carson -- Ben Carson, presser yesterday, you would know this well, where he says I'm talking to the president, he wants to help out. He would even meet with Elijah Cummings himself. I think he wants to solve the problem. I was talking to Dana today on the show, and I think this thing could turn out for the better.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: The coalition of African-American pastors meeting with Trump, and they're going to Baltimore?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: These are moments when you can actually have an opportunity to do something. And if the president is willing to meet -- you could probably do something. Here's something, though, this has been going on for a long time.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Elijah Cummings talked about that in 1999, that's 20 years ago, it's 2019. A lot of this can't necessarily be fixed by the government.  The government can throw money at things, but it's not actually a government thing, this is a deeper problem, and we should get Marianne Williamson on it.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Oh, she'll get Bill Pulte.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yeah. There's a lot of things, it's not just the government.  It's --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Bill Pulte, I think, is already -- is looking at Baltimore.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: -- St. Louis with the dude from twitter. And he, obviously --

utterances.speaker: KILMEADE
utterances.utterance: They flag down houses and rebuild --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes, the blight authority.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: As a constituent on the West Coast, my biggest issue with this is that the taking offense trigger blocks the actual facts.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Good point.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: Because the reality is a blight on government, right. Reality is that blight on Elijah Cummings, the fact that he's been the representative there for decades and nothing has changed. So, for example in Seattle where I pay my taxes, the mayor there that - the Police Department and the City Attorney released a statistic that said look over 80 percent of the homeless are drug addled. And the Mayor goes, no, no, it's only one in three, because that would reflect poorly on her. Right. And me and Dr. Drew, the 5 percent Dr. Drew and I down to Los Angeles, we've got a whole package over the weekend and we covered Skid Row and the homelessness issue down there which is in actuality a drug addict and as he says, a mental illness issue. But here we have the Mayor down there saying, it's all about housing, affordable housing. And thank goodness, we took a first step today to implement my comprehensive plan of action, because it's only about them. It's never about the triage.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: If you solve, but you don't get any more money.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: Exactly. And also, that there is no triage accounted for because that's something that isn't part of a plan.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Did you--

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: KILMEADE
